The fourfold model is a bilinear model that categorizes acculturation strategies along two dimensions. The first dimension concerns the retention or rejection of an individual's minority or native culture (i.e. "Is it considered to be of value to maintain one's identity and characteristics?"), whereas the second dimension concerns the adoption or rejection of the dominant group or host culture. ("Is it considered to be of value to maintain relationships with the larger society?") From this, four acculturation strategies emerge.<ref name=":0">{{cite journal|title=Immigration, Acculturation, and Adaptation|last=Berry|first=John W.|journal=[[Applied_Psychology_(journal)|Applied Psychology]]|issue=1|doi=10.1111/j.1464-0597.1997.tb01087.x|year=1997|volume=46|page=10}}</ref>

* '''[[同化|同化]]'''  occurs when individuals adopt the cultural norms of a dominant or host culture, over their original culture. Sometimes it is [[Forced_assimilation|forced]] by governments.
* '''[[种族隔离|排外]]''' occurs when individuals reject the dominant or host culture in favor of preserving their culture of origin. Separation is often facilitated by immigration to [[ethnic_enclaves|ethnic enclaves]].
* '''[[Racial_integration|整合]]''' occurs when individuals are able to adopt the cultural norms of the dominant or host culture while maintaining their culture of origin. Integration leads to, and is often synonymous with [[biculturalism|biculturalism]].
* [[社会排斥|解構]] occurs when individuals reject both their culture of origin and the dominant host culture.

Studies suggest that individuals' respective acculturation strategy can differ between their private and public life spheres.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Domains and dimensions in acculturation: Implicit theories of Turkish–Dutch|last=Arends-Tóth|first=Judit|date=February 2004|journal=International Journal of Intercultural Relations|issue=1|doi=10.1016/j.ijintrel.2003.09.001|volume=28|pages=19–35|author2=van de Vijver, Fons J. R.}}</ref> For instance, an individual may reject the values and norms of the dominant culture in his private life (separation), whereas he might adapt to the dominant culture in public parts of his life (i.e., integration or assimilation).
